### 1. One-Line Summary
Rakza Z is the spinnier, tackier, more controlled hybrid rubber for deliberate spin-first play, while Dignics 80 is the faster, more elastic, more balanced high-end tensor for aggressive two-wing topspin and countering.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rakza Z is less bouncy on soft touch and short strokes because of its sticky topsheet and hard hybrid character, so it feels calmer in the short game. Dignics 80 engages more easily and gives more free speed at medium input.
    * **Top End:** Dignics 80 has the higher outright top-end pace; Butterfly rates it faster than Rakza Z, and its Spring Sponge X is built for elastic acceleration from mid-distance.
    * **Linearity:** Rakza Z is generally more linear and predictable from soft to hard impact. Dignics 80 has a stronger catapult once you compress the sponge.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Rakza Z has the clearer advantage on opening against backspin because the tacky topsheet grabs the ball more directly and helps lift heavy underspin with confidence.
    * **Max Spin:** On full acceleration, both can produce very high spin, but they do it differently: Rakza Z leans more on topsheet grip/tack, while Dignics 80 leans more on elastic deformation and sponge rebound. In pure serve and first-loop spin, Rakza Z usually has the edge; in fast topspin exchanges, Dignics 80 sustains heavy spin at higher pace more easily.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Rakza Z is explicitly a sticky inverted rubber; Dignics 80 is a high-friction, non-tacky high-tension rubber. That difference is the core reason their spin behavior feels different.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Both are on the higher-arc side, but Rakza Z typically gives the more pronounced, spin-lifted arc on opening loops, while Dignics 80 gives a cleaner offensive arc in topspin-to-topspin play. Yasaka lists Rakza Z as “High” arc, and Butterfly highlights Dignics 80’s high arc versus Tenergy 80.
    * **Safety:** Rakza Z is usually safer over the net on slow-to-medium spin openings. Dignics 80 is safer when you commit positively and play through the ball with active acceleration.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rakza Z feels firmer, tackier, and more “grabby,” with a distinctly hybrid / semi-Chinese style feedback. Dignics 80 feels cleaner, more elastic, and more modern Butterfly-style at impact.
    * **Dwell:** Dignics 80 is explicitly marketed as having increased dwell time from Spring Sponge X, but in play the dwell sensation is different: Rakza Z feels like the topsheet holds the ball, whereas Dignics 80 feels like the sponge and sheet deform together more elastically.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Rakza Z is usually less reactive to incoming spin in passive touch because the tacky, lower-bounce behavior keeps the ball shorter. Dignics 80 is not wild, but it is livelier and asks for finer hand control in receive and drop shots.
    * **Touch Play:** Rakza Z is the better pure short-game rubber of the two for serve, stop, short push, and loaded receive. Dignics 80 is still good, but it rewards active, precise touch rather than simply damping the ball.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rakza Z tends to absorb pace a bit better and can feel more secure on simple passive blocks. Dignics 80 is stable, but because it is faster and more elastic, passive blocks can carry longer unless your angle is well set.
    * **Active Counter:** Dignics 80 is stronger for active counter-topspin and counter-drive, especially away from the table, because it has more free rebound and better high-speed continuity. Rakza Z can counter well, but it is more work-intensive and rewards fuller technique.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Rakza Z if:**
    * You want a hybrid rubber with real tack, stronger serve/receive spin, and better short-game restraint.
    * Your priority is opening quality, spin variation, and a more deliberate forehand-oriented game.
    * You prefer a more linear response and do not want as much built-in catapult.
    * You are coming from Chinese or hybrid rubbers and want something easier than a full Chinese setup without losing too much grip identity.

* **Choose Dignics 80 if:**
    * You want the more complete modern offensive rubber across looping, countering, blocking, and mid-distance play.
    * You value easier pace, stronger active counters, and a more balanced speed-spin profile than a tacky hybrid.
    * You play an aggressive two-wing topspin game and want one rubber that adapts well from close to mid-distance.
    * You are comfortable paying a premium for top-end elasticity and overall versatility. Butterfly currently lists Dignics 80 at $93.99 on its official store.
